  "prompt": "What is G box?",
  "response": "A G box (or G-box) is a specific DNA sequence motif found in the promoter regions of many genes, particularly in plants. It is typically recognized by certain transcription factors and plays a crucial role in gene regulation. Key points about G boxes include:\n\n1. Sequence: The consensus sequence is typically CACGTG or variations of it\n\n2. Location: Usually found in promoter regions of genes\n\n3. Function:\n- Involved in gene expression regulation\n- Helps control transcription of genes\n- Plays a significant role in responding to environmental signals\n- Important in light-regulated gene expression\n\n4. Binding proteins: Often recognized by transcription factors like bZIP (basic leucine zipper) proteins\n\n5. Significance: Particularly important in plant biology, where they help regulate processes like photosynthesis, stress response, and development\n\nG boxes are considered important cis-regulatory elements that help control gene expression by allowing specific proteins to bind and influence transcription.",
